NEWCASTLE DISEASE - CZECH REPUBLIC
==================================
Date: Fri, 23 May 1997
From: Dorothy Preslar <dpreslar@fas.org>
Source: OIE Disease Status Report Vol. 10 - No. 21
The first outbreak of Newcastle disease in the Czech Republic since June
1996 has prompted an emergency report.
Text of a fax received on 21 May 1997 from Dr L. Deleda, Deputy Director of
the State Veterinary Administration,Prague:
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, post mortem and laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 19 May 1997.
Estimated date of first infection: 12 May 1997.
Location: Lhota u Dobran, Plzen-jih district (in the south-west of the country)
Number of outbreaks: 1
Description of affected population: backyard flock.
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
susceptible cases deaths destroyed slaughtered
7 2 2 5 0
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: State Veterinary Institute, Prague.
B. Diagnostic tests used: virus isolation.
C. Causal agent: paramyxovirus-1.
Source of agent / origin of infection: unknown.
Control measures during reporting period: stamping out; 3-km-radius
restriction zone around the outbreak and movement controls within a 10-km
radius; vaccination and surveillance.
--
Dorothy B. Preslar
